Student performance

guilinXue

2020/6/13

###Introduction Hi Friends, welcome to my kernel! I have used dplyr and ggplot2 to manipulate and visualise the student performance data. I have then created a random forest to create a simple prediction model. If you find this script useful, please upvote or leave a comment with your feedback, Thanks!

Loading data and libraries

key libraries used include:

ggplot2 - Data visualisation

dplyr - Data manipulation

kableExtra, xtable - Creating tables

RColorBrewer - Using colours

> 
> Data <- read.csv("StudentsPerformance.csv", header = TRUE)
> library(kableExtra)
> library(xtable)
> library(RColorBrewer)
> library(ggplot2)
> library(dplyr)
> library(tidyr)

Understanding the data

The data has eight variables and 1000 observations. The key variables include gender, race/ethnicity, parental level of education,lunch, test preparation course, math score, reading score and writing score.

> str(Data)
  'data.frame': 1000 obs. of  8 variables:
   $ gender                     : chr  "female" "female" "female" "male" ...
   $ race.ethnicity             : chr  "group B" "group C" "group B" "group A" ...
   $ parental.level.of.education: chr  "bachelor's degree" "some college" "master's degree" "associate's degree" ...
   $ lunch                      : chr  "standard" "standard" "standard" "free/reduced" ...
   $ test.preparation.course    : chr  "none" "completed" "none" "none" ...
   $ math.score                 : int  72 69 90 47 76 71 88 40 64 38 ...
   $ reading.score              : int  72 90 95 57 78 83 95 43 64 60 ...
   $ writing.score              : int  74 88 93 44 75 78 92 39 67 50 ...

Exploratory data analysis

  1. Students By gender: There are more 518 female students and 482 male students.
> plot1 <- ggplot() + geom_bar(data = Data, aes(x = Data$gender), width = 0.2, fill = "green") + 
+     geom_text(stat = "count", data = Data, aes(x = Data$gender, label = ..count..), 
+         vjust = -0.2) + theme_bw() + xlab("Gender") + ylab("Number of Students") + 
+     theme_classic() + ggtitle("Number of Students by Gender") + scale_fill_brewer(type = "qual", 
+     palette = 1, direction = 1, aesthetics = "fill") + ylim(0, 600)
> 
> plot1

  1. Students By race: There are 319 students in group C, 262 students in group D while there are only 89 students in group A.
> plot2 <- ggplot() + geom_bar(data = Data, aes(x = Data$race.ethnicity), width = 0.6, 
+     fill = "green") + geom_text(data = Data, aes(x = Data$race.ethnicity, label = ..count..), 
+     stat = "count", vjust = -0.2) + theme_bw() + xlab("Race/Ethnicity") + ylab("Number of Students") + 
+     theme(text = element_text(family = "Tahoma")) + theme_classic() + scale_fill_brewer(type = "qual", 
+     palette = 1, direction = 1, aesthetics = "fill") + ggtitle("Number of Students by Race/Ethnicity")
> plot2

  1. Distribution of scores 152 students scored between 65 - 70 marks in maths. 154 students scored in the same bracket in writing. 148 students scored between 70 - 75 marks in reading.
> Data_gather <- Data %>% mutate(StudentID = row_number()) %>% gather(key = "subject", 
+     value = "score", math.score:writing.score)
> 
> Data_gather %>% ggplot(aes(x = score)) + geom_histogram(bins = 20, colour = "green", 
+     fill = "white") + facet_grid(subject ~ .) + theme_bw() + theme_classic() + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 
+     100), breaks = seq(0, 100, 10)) + # geom_label(aes(label = ..count..), stat = 'count', y = 150, size = 2) +
+ stat_bin(bins = 20, geom = "text", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = -1) + ylim(0, 
+     200)

Preparation courses

  1. Completion: Majority of students do not complete preparation courses. Proportion of students completing preparation course is highest in group E.
> plot3 <- ggplot() + geom_bar(data = Data, aes(x = Data$test.preparation.course), 
+     width = 0.6, fill = "green") + geom_text(data = Data, aes(x = Data$test.preparation.course, 
+     label = ..count..), stat = "count", vjust = -0.2) + # geom_bar(data = Data, aes(x = Data$test.preparation.course, y =
+ # race.ethnicity), fill = '#bcd4e6', width = 0.6) +
+ facet_grid(. ~ race.ethnicity) + theme_bw() + xlab("Preparation course") + ylab("Number of Students") +

+     scale_fill_brewer(type = "qual", palette = 1, direction = 1, aesthetics = "fill")
> 
> plot3

  1. Impact of course: As we see the that the average of the scores of students who completed preparation course is higher than the average of scores of the students who did not complete the course.
> plot4 <- ggplot(data = Data_gather, aes(x = Data_gather$test.preparation.course, 
+     y = Data_gather$score, fill = Data_gather$test.preparation.course)) + geom_boxplot() +

Correlation between reading and writing score

There is a strong correlation between reading scores and the writing scores with a coefficient of 0.95.

Prediction

We created a simple prediction model, to see if we predict whether the student had a test preparation course or not based on all other variables.

> library(randomForest)
> library(caret)
> Data1 <- Data
> 
> Data1$gender <- as.numeric(factor(Data1$gender, levels = unique(Data1$gender)))
> Data1$race.ethnicity <- as.numeric(factor(Data1$race.ethnicity, levels = unique(Data1$race.ethnicity)))
> Data1$parental.level.of.education <- as.numeric(factor(Data1$parental.level.of.education, 
+     levels = unique(Data1$parental.level.of.education)))
> Data1$lunch <- as.numeric(factor(Data1$lunch, levels = unique(Data1$lunch)))
> Data1$test.preparation.course <- as.numeric(factor(Data1$test.preparation.course, 
+     levels = unique(Data1$test.preparation.course)))
> Data1$test.preparation.course = as.factor(Data1$test.preparation.course)

Lets divide the set into training and test set with 70% of the records in the training set and the remaining in the test set.

> set.seed(125)
> train <- sample(nrow(Data1), 0.7 * nrow(Data1), replace = FALSE)
> 
> TrainingSet <- Data1[train, ]
> TestSet <- Data1[-train, ]
> 
> str(TrainingSet)
  'data.frame': 700 obs. of  8 variables:
   $ gender                     : num  1 2 1 1 1 2 1 2 2 1 ...
   $ race.ethnicity             : num  5 3 5 2 4 1 2 4 2 4 ...
   $ parental.level.of.education: num  4 4 4 4 2 5 1 5 5 6 ...
   $ lunch                      : num  2 2 1 1 2 1 1 1 2 2 ...
   $ test.preparation.course    : Factor w/ 2 levels "1","2": 1 2 1 1 1 1 2 1 1 2 ...
   $ math.score                 : int  70 79 66 66 60 82 79 76 59 35 ...
   $ reading.score              : int  84 82 65 77 66 82 92 73 53 55 ...
   $ writing.score              : int  81 82 69 73 70 80 89 68 52 60 ...
> str(TestSet)
  'data.frame': 300 obs. of  8 variables:
   $ gender                     : num  1 1 1 2 2 2 1 1 2 1 ...
   $ race.ethnicity             : num  2 1 1 4 3 2 2 1 4 2 ...
   $ parental.level.of.education: num  2 3 4 4 2 5 4 2 1 1 ...
   $ lunch                      : num  1 1 1 1 1 1 2 2 2 1 ...
   $ test.preparation.course    : Factor w/ 2 levels "1","2": 2 1 1 1 2 1 1 2 2 1 ...
   $ math.score                 : int  69 90 71 40 78 88 54 65 74 67 ...
   $ reading.score              : int  90 95 83 52 72 89 58 75 71 69 ...
   $ writing.score              : int  88 93 78 43 70 86 61 70 80 75 ...

Here is a simple random forest model that has an accuracy of 71.67%.

> model1 <- randomForest(test.preparation.course ~ ., data = TrainingSet, importance = TRUE, 
+     ntree = 500, mtry = 6)
> model1
  
  Call:
   randomForest(formula = test.preparation.course ~ ., data = TrainingSet,      importance = TRUE, ntree = 500, mtry = 6) 
                 Type of random forest: classification
                       Number of trees: 500

          OOB estimate of  error rate: 34.29%

  2 153 102   0.6000000

> PredTest <- predict(model1, TestSet, type = "class")
> mean(PredTest == TestSet$test.preparation.course)
  [1] 0.7266667
